title.narrative: Power to Youth - Indonesia

description.narrative: Power to You(th) is a five-year program from 2021 - 2025, the Power to You(th) programme (PTY) will empower adolescent girls and young women (AGYW) to increase their agency, claim their rights, address gender inequalities, challenge gender norms, and advocate for inclusive decision-making. As a result, harmful practices such as female genital mutilation/ cutting (FGM/C) and child marriage (CM), sexual and gender-based violence (SGBV), and unintended pregnancies will be decreased

title.narrative: PATHWAY 4: Policies and policy implementation
# of (inter)national laws, policies, norms and practices implemented to decrease barriers to SRHR and prevent harmful practices, and SGBV (SCS 1)

comment.narrative: All four villages in Jember have successfully issued a decree on the Children's Village Forum. One of them even has allocated the Village Children's Forum budget in the RAPBDes (Village Development Budget).

title.narrative: PATHWAY 2: Strengthening civil society
# of communities,CSOs, and advocacy networks with increased lobbying, advocating, thematic and/or research capabilities (SCS 5, SRHR J)

comment.narrative: At the CSOs level, young people have been trained regarding the issues of SRHR, GTA, SGBV and used it for lobbying, advocating, and communicating with related stakeholders.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 2: Strengthening civil society
# of CSOs who have advanced on using a Gender and Social Inclusion lens during all phases of the programming cycle with specific attention to youth (SCS 8)

comment.narrative: CSOs within CMT Indonesia have a long-standing experience in implementing development programs to gender, child protection and community organization, as well as SDGs issues. Thus, when we strengthen their capacity, some expected achievements have already been done. However, we do realize that they need regular technical assistance and capacity strengthening to involve more men, people with disabilities and people with diverse SOGIESC in program activities.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 2: Strengthening civil society
# of CSOs participating in Power to You(th) (SCS 6)

comment.narrative: In 2021, Rutgers Indonesia selected three new partners for the implementation of Power to Youth Indonesia: Rutgers Indonesia; 2030 Youth Force; TANOKER; SEMAK.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 4: Policies and policy implementation
# of media reports on PtY key issues that influence public and political debate

comment.narrative:
Rutgers Indonesia trained 10 journalists through media fellowship to increase their knowledge and capacity on SRHR and SGBV perspective. These journalists then help the program to increase our media coverage. Most of the news written consistently consist of positive messages which help to raise the awareness of PTY’s issues and the importance of CSE in preventing SGBV.
At the local level, some reports written by the media are mostly about the activities and progress of program implementation, for example, the dissemination of baseline study, socialization of programs and dialogues between CSOs partners and government stakeholders.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 2: Strengthening civil society

# of times government or private sector at all levels include CSOs in decision making processes related to our advocacy issues, react to CSO positions by adopting their argumentation, or putting our advocacy issues on the agenda

comment.narrative:
Targets for 2021 have not been made for this outcome but communication and relationship have been well established between CSOs, government, and other CSOs outside PtY’s coalition as PtY often asked to be involved in CSOs and government network activity that led to creating space to engage more with them.
The involvement of our partners in the public discussion with the government and other CSOs is due to their experiences in implementing development programs in the respective three districts. The selection processes put the criteria on how PTY CSO partners should already have a prominent reputation within the issue of development. Thus, the involvement has already been a lot during the first year of implementation.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 2: Strengthening civil society
# and type of advocacy initiatives carried out by CSOs for, by or with their membership/constituency

comment.narrative: Targets for 2021 have not been made for this outcome but partners have already received commitments from other CSOs outside PtY coalition as a start to implement the advocacy of PtY programs next year.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 1: Strengthening youth to claim civic space
# of young people (disaggregate by gender identity (f/m/x)) who participate in policy and decision-making bodies (disaggregate type and level) and perceive their participation as meaningful (SRHR A)

comment.narrative: We expect to achieve this in upcoming years of program implementation, while we are continuously strengthening young people's capacity so that they will meaningfully participate in decision-making processes at the village, sub-district, district and national levels.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 4: Policies and policy implementation

# and type of (inter)national laws and policies blocked, adopted, maintained, improved including the number of detrimental policies which are prevented or blocked from adoption or development to decrease barriers to SRHR and prevent harmful practices and SGBV (SCS 2, SRHR H)

comment.narrative: We achieved the signing of 4 MoUs. There is a three-year MoU between the East Lombok district government and Rutgers Lombok consisting of support and permission for implementing the PtY program. In addition, there are three more MoU between Rutgers and district-level offices, which are the Health Service and the East Lombok District Education Office.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 2: Strengthening civil society
Description of effective use of accountability mechanisms by citizens/communities and CSOs towards SRHR of all people (SRHR I)

comment.narrative: In 2021 there were no activities for this target, because CMT Indonesia was still trying to identify and map what accountability mechanisms are available in program respective areas. Several mechanisms were qualitatively identified, but in some areas, these mechanisms still need to be encouraged to be established by the local government with various elements in the community, for example, mechanisms related to child marriage cases. Some regions still do not have a mechanism by which the community, especially young people, can hold the government accountable for addressing these issues.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 4: Policies and policy implementation
Level of public support for family planning and prevention of harmful practices and SGBV

comment.narrative: In this year, there were some activities targeting social actors at the district levels. Religious and community leaders, teachers and health workers give their support to the Power to Youth program. During these socializations, participants gave several questions and input in the event for the program. In a bigger picture, the support has been built for the first year, but has to be maintained and further clarified when it comes to the specific program issues. In 2022, there will be more activities contributing to this target.

title.narrative: PATHWAY 4: Policies and policy implementation
Whether or not legal frameworks are in place to promote, enforce, implement and monitor equality and non-discrimination on the basis of sex

comment.narrative: We perceive that there were no activities contributing to this target in 2021.
